# Backend root URL — must match the mobile app’s EXPO_PUBLIC_BACKEND_URL.
# Spring Boot uses server.servlet.context-path=/api, so a direct URL must end with /api.
#
# --- HTTPS site + HTTP-only EC2 (no TLS on the JVM) ---
# Do NOT use https://YOUR_EC2_IP:8080 — nothing serves TLS on the raw IP.
#
# Option A (quick): Vercel serverless proxy (see api/trivaller-backend/[...path].js)
#   1) Vercel → Environment Variables → BACKEND_HTTP_ORIGIN=http://YOUR_EC2_IP:8080  (no /api)
#   2) Production build env: VITE_API_BASE_URL=/api/trivaller-backend
#   The browser calls https://trivaller.com/api/trivaller-backend/... ; Vercel forwards to EC2.
#
# Option B (proper): nginx + DNS + Let’s Encrypt on the API host, then:
#   VITE_API_BASE_URL=https://api.yourdomain.com/api
#
# If the marketing site is HTTPS and you point VITE_API_BASE_URL at http://…, the browser blocks
# mixed content. Use Option A or B.
#
# Local dev with the same proxy path (Vite forwards to Spring):
#   VITE_API_BASE_URL=/api/trivaller-backend
#   Optional: VITE_DEV_BACKEND_ORIGIN=http://127.0.0.1:8081
#
# Examples (direct to Spring — OK for HTTP localhost page or HTTPS API):
#   VITE_API_BASE_URL=https://api.trivaller.com/api
#   VITE_API_BASE_URL=http://localhost:8081/api
#
# Set VITE_* in your host (Vercel / Netlify / etc.) for production builds.
#
# Local website dev (npm run dev): copy to .env — port must match a RUNNING backend.
# Spring default in application.properties is 8081; your machine may use 8080.
# VITE_API_BASE_URL=http://localhost:8081/api
# VITE_API_BASE_URL=http://localhost:8080/api
#
# Point at EC2 over plain HTTP from local dev only (HTTP page → HTTP API is OK).
# Do not use this when the site is served over HTTPS — use an https:// API URL instead.
# Do not use https:// with a bare IP (e.g. https://1.2.3.4:8080) — use /api/trivaller-backend proxy or a real TLS host.
# VITE_API_BASE_URL=http://YOUR_EC2_PUBLIC_IP:8080/api
VITE_API_BASE_URL=http://localhost:8081/api
